column447:
27/Aug/25 12:20 PM;poty002;Hi Team,
I've investigated the issue.
This is a {*}data integrity issue{*}. The table *{{mmb_packaging_metadata}}* is modeled as *One-to-One* with {*}{{packaging_masters}}{*}, but *two rows* exist for the same master, causing downstream logic to fail when a single record is expected.
 * *Product:* {{19802955941}}

 * *Master (packaging_masters.id):* {{27388326}}

 * *Problem:* two {{mmb_packaging_metadata}} rows reference the same {{{}packaging_master_id = 27388326{}}}.



Affected flow:
*Product → ProductLinks → Master (27388326) → PackagingMaster → MMBMetadata*
After {{{}DirectUploadMasterSelectionAction{}}}, we enter {{{}DirectUploadViewAction{}}}, which loads PackagingMaster → *MMBMetadata* and expects *exactly one* row. Because two rows exist, the view/logic fails (e.g., non-unique result, ambiguous selection, or assertion on 1–1 mapping).

Diagnosis SQL (examples)
select * from masters m inner join product_links pl on m.master_id = pl.master_id where pl.product_id = 10916723;
select * from packaging_masters pm inner join masters m on pm.master_id = m.master_id where m.master_id = 27388326;
select * from mmb_packaging_metadata mmb inner join packaging_masters pm on mmb.master_id = pm.master_id where pm.master_id = 27388326;

Proposed fix: Data cleanup (one-time)

Thanks;;;

